A Republican Strategy to Counter Obama's Re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of US governments promulgated new laws from 2009 making the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon gained momentum after the November 2010 elections, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in 2011 alone.
The new election laws require voters to present a photo ID card and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce advance voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on election day and deprive citizens with a judicial record of their right to vote.
Before the 2006 election, no state required voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to do so.
In 2008, the Supreme Court of the United States upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law.
The Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card like the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity document.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required identity card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
Much more.
Students, voters considered to vote more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID card issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs to vote.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to do so.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voting.
However, it appears that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
Republican lawmakers sponsored laws in 2011 that abolished voter registration on election day in eight states.
In addition, they have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to electors wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to register about 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the registration rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the advance voting period.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the state’s voters.
The same goes for Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
On the other hand, white voters who made up 76% of the electorate accounted for only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have vigorously opposed legislation restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by Democratic governors’ vetoes.
The Attorney General of the United States has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have laws requiring the presentation of photo identification cards.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that were passed and see it as an obvious goal to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that passed these laws accounted for 171 of the 270 votes needed by the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes in the electoral system will have significant impacts on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Prostate cancer screening: take the test or not?
Indeed, the PSA test would sometimes present erroneous results, with false negative results or false positives, which lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
What make hesitate even more men already reluctant to pass screening tests.
Pass the test or not?
We asked for the advice of two experts.
In studies conducted in the United States, there was a lot of contamination between control groups, so it is difficult to interpret these data and have firm recommendations.
Another European study concluded that there was a difference in mortality between patients who were screened and those who were not screened.
This study also showed, with a follow-up after 12 years, that we are between 30 and 40% more likely to have metastases if we are not detected.
So I recommend the test from age 50, or from age 40 if you have a direct parent who has already had prostate cancer.
Men of African-American descent are also at greater risk.
The key is to make the right decision once cancer has been detected.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are indolent.
There is a real need to make the patient understand the degree of risk of their cancer, by offering them options, by not necessarily treating prostate cancers that do not affect life in the long term, and by opting instead, in these cases, for active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men in whom cancer is detected will not be treated, because their cancer is not aggressive and does not threaten their lives.
We're going to suggest active surveillance and if the disease progresses, we're going to offer them treatment.
Increasingly, criteria for deciding who should or should not be treated are being determined with precision.
I still recommend taking the test.
But the important thing is to have a discussion with your doctor to determine if you should pass it or not.
