The Higgs boson
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created quite a stir, last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worst" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists, it’s still not entirely clear whether it’s the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we are holding an authentic new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, but data is still missing to be perfectly sure.
Let's suppose it's the Higgs, since the chances of getting it wrong seem slim, and let's see what it's all about.
There is, in this world, a fatally inescapable law that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
Even though particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it too has a law of this kind: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting roughly of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In a corner there are good citizens named fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And in the other are the bosons, a dirty band of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not for this principle, which means they can be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, for that matter) The Particle Adventure, Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not address here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, it must be emphasized here, are not all as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of an extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “disrupts” the electromagnetic field in this precise place, much like a rock thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" arises an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore, one of the bosons "force carriers".
More stable field
The same goes with the Higgs boson, except that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, one must reach very, very high energies, a little as if it were a frozen pond of which only a very large rock could ride the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN's - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring 27 km in circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful in explaining the relationship between Higgs and mass.
Not all particles, not all materials, interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don't - a piece of paper, for example, will never stand on its own on a fridge.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, hold) do not.
Now, what can "bring" all this research, asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancies between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
Many of them are eager to find one, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "new physics" and plug some holes of the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has huge deficiencies, offering no explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-oops!).
But such discrepancies have not been found at CERN until now.
Impacts
The impact of this research on the daily lives of Mr. and Mrs. Tout-le-Monde is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be none.
At the very beginning of the 1960s, the pioneers of the laser, in Bell Laboratories, had no suspicion of the revolution that their work was going to trigger.
They were looking for scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 -, initially the laser was rather seen as a "lab gadget".
Imagine...
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his optical work.
This sensor, although not at all its original intent, now serves as an "eye" to all the world's digital cameras, and earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This doesn’t mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, you never know...
Palliative Care - The Best Way to Die...
With its Commission on Dying with Dignity, Quebec recently debated the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is set to resume shortly as a bill is prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this crucial area.
Le Devoir tried to take a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that gnawed at him had left him a respite of two years.
"They had given me five years to live, I was seven years old," he said, half-fig half-raisin, lying in bed at the Victor-Gadbois hospice in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for that,” he says.
Illness does its job: a huge weakness that prevents it from going to the toilet alone, and even eating alone.
Sitting in front of an appetizing lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even manages to smile, talks to strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicines, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My greatest wish is for people to cure me of diarrhea, it’s humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In our lifetime, we learn that a man pisses standing," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois house.
Restoring to the stage of the child, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
“It depends on the person’s ability to accept regression,” he notes.
Because, in the opinion of many people working in palliative care, great moments are taking place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this point, the “team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provides so-called “curative” care.
For 89-year-old A., the worst fear is to die "conscious and suffocated".
But the disease made me discover my children.
“I have good children,” she adds.
“I don’t have any wishes in life anymore,” she says, before accepting to be put on a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days, however, she awaits a final visit from her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, body care and food assistance are provided with a group of volunteers.
It is palliative care, which is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little when you know that we all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the house.
Whether in terms of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
To the dying, we will agree to provide mouth care to the brandy or Pepsi, according to the request.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, who died during the night.
This morning, it is his son who will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help loved ones as much as patients," says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days follow each other but are not the same.
Next to a 93-year-old old man enjoying his last family gathering in the courtyard, snug in his pillows while toasting in his honor, a 36-year-old boy is tragically dying, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, after trying everything to survive.
“For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds that are occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home arrive from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Access to Palliative Care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal phase of his life, whether at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Greater Montreal Hospice Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec health care that makes several doctors specializing in palliative care fear the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care leaders including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to show their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone will have the right to quality palliative care before we agree to proceed with euthanasia.
Recently, she said, I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room, in great pain, without doing what was necessary to relieve her.
I fear that patients are only asking to die because they are not receiving the right care.
And at the same time, several oncologists are scrambling on their patients until the last day, despite the worst predictions.
Hélène Richard’s survival expectations were already minimal when she gave up trying chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she said.
She told me I was finished!
Not almighty care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank the caregivers for not having acceded to their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, Director of Palliative Care at the Greater Montreal Hospice Palliative Care Society, patients are reported to be refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which is equivalent to putting the patient to sleep until the time of his death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear this part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
Patients who are not relieved always say the same sentence: “I want to die.”
But it doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” it means “I want to be relieved.”
