With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
The opposite of current currency exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between stakeholders.
Moreover, as often in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the belief that the current monetary system, made up of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol in the manner of BitTorrent, which allows the exchange of files from peer to peer.
About 200,000 transactions have already been recorded through 15,000 computers on the network.
A few thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a means of payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a peak of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, dropped to 2 dollars, five months later, before returning today around ten dollars (the prices are listed on the site bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing very impressive, compared to global trade in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency”, “in competition with the dollar or the euro” and “similar to conventional currencies”.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currency such as “credits”, used to progress in a video game that you win by playing or that you can buy (and sometimes exchange in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this kind of system.
But, each time, a central authority controls and processes the exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all nodes in the network are both account book custodians, auditors, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually done between two email addresses in the manner of an email.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double key encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins exchanged exist in the public book of accounts, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge to computers, and whose winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a hashing phase of a file, that is, transforming a large file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "hashing" the whole thing.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily check that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, to defraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphan because the two have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge won 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred millionth, which leaves margin...
The difficulty of the challenge is also met with each increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already had its ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in deposits stolen.
“The flaw used is not about the protocol itself,” says Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the potential for money laundering through this anonymous service.
Cash also has this defect.
Prominent actors like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the ledger and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, "giant sales" were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of an educational book on this currency, believes very much in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are cheaper.
The holder also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement among merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
All they have to do is communicate an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize", says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
“It will take time for Bitcoin to win, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicted.
The ECB, in its report, also plans to re-evaluate the various risks, now considered high, if this currency succeeds.
We left Afghanistan.
And then what?
French troops have left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the US are expected to follow suit by the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to regain possession of its territory and for the Afghans to choose their future, without expecting anything from us.
It is mainly the Afghan peasants that we have punished by considering them terrorists.
And ourselves, with our 88 soldiers killed, and the wounded, the maimed.
The Taliban consists of foreign extremists, former refugee leaders in Pakistan, but often peasants who refuse the foreign armed presence, as in the days of the Soviets.
They want to defend their traditions, ancient and archaic, even if they have been joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajiks.
Tolerated, sometimes helped by local insurgents, these will no longer be when Westerners become more discreet.
The departure of the French troops from the base of Nijrab, which I observed from the hills planted with almond trees thanks to French credits, was in order.
The convoys of trucks and armored vehicles reached Kabul without being attacked, overflew by helicopters.
There will be no Taliban surge in Kabul by the end of 2014.
Circumstances have changed since their irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996.
Kabul was then empty, the country with fire and blood because of the struggles between different factions.
Their takeover of the country was then perceived as a kind of liberation, a return to security.
The Afghan women paid the price for the obscurantism of these peasants who were overtaken by the Al-Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved today.
Former mujahideen, Afghan government and current Taliban join in the desire to keep women in a lower position.
The leading figures of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They turned into businessmen, seizing government land and selling it as building land to refugees returning from Iran and Pakistan, benefiting from huge U.S. subcontracts.
Most of them did not fight on their own.
People, as I have heard in the countryside, aspire to a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave, as will those who have taken advantage of American largesse: the flight of capital is considerable.
Young people are tired of war and its ideologies.
They have been around the modern world during their exiles in Iran or Pakistan, they have appreciated the benefits.
About 65% of the population is under the age of 25; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, one-fifth of the total population.
In cities, government schools are full of girls and boys alike.
It will be necessary to provide work for these young people who will no longer want to return to the obscurantism of the old parties or the corruption of certain leaders.
All of them, including armed opponents, are fond of cell phones; television, and its Turkish soap operas that present a modern world, is followed everywhere.
The army is now present.
Will the authorities who will order it be considered legitimate?
Former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are already concerned with reconstituting provincial militias, which will escape the central power.
Afghanistan, a country of mountains, with strong local identities, should be able to benefit from a certain decentralization, like the Western nations, but the United States wanted to transform it into a centralized state, with strong presidential power, removing the post of Prime Minister that existed since the Constitution of 1964.
President Karzai does not want foreign controls, especially during the elections scheduled for April 2014.
But his country has been dependent on foreign aid since the 1950s and well before.
No industry has been restarted, no dams are in repair, no major irrigation systems are being repaired.
Everything is imported; nothing is produced except fruits and vegetables.
Priority is left to private initiative.
In a country ruined by thirty years of war, government control over infrastructure would have been necessary.
There was widespread rumour that Afghanistan had immense mineral wealth.
This only added to the feeling that Westerners were only there to seize it.
Without energy to process iron or copper ore on site, nor means of transport to export it through the mountains, there is no mining.
The Chinese have already almost left the Mes Aynak copper mine, leaving international archaeologists (financed by the World Bank) to excavate the huge Buddhist site and remain the largest employers in the province.
Afghanistan and Pakistan, which are heavily dependent on imports and exports, will also have to restore normal relations.
The departure of the French fighting troops ended on 20 November.
The new cooperation treaty provides for the continuation of traditional aids: high school for girls, boys, department of French at the university, French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support to the Archaeological Delegation.
Since 2009, in an attempt to "win hearts and minds" and to carry out the impossible task of matching aid and offensive actions, a service of "civilo-military actions" of the Ministry of Defence (Cimic), suppressed in 2012, has carried out, and had carried out by a small French NGO, many works of collective interest and agricultural rehabilitation actions in dozens of mountain villages.
These works, greedy in local labor, were able to help contain the insurrection: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increase of arable land.
What will we leave as a memory, after two billion euros of military spending?
A much more modest budget would contribute to the improvement of local living conditions, very hard in these valleys often located at more than 2,000 meters above sea level.
The embassy received dozens of written requests for small agricultural achievements from local communities in Kapisa province.
In order for them to free themselves from the insurgency led by foreign groups, which the farmers have told me they want, a small, well-controlled and directly affecting civilian aid should be maintained in their favour.
A Constitution at the Forceps in Egypt
This is another poker shot by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it full powers, it has decided to play its all-out.
Taking everyone by surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State gave this Assembly two more months to complete its work.
Egypt has been relying on a provisional text for almost two years, several times amended, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal blunders.
This new initiative has only increased the divide in the country.
For his opponents, the President perseveres in his "autocratic delirium", continuing to "betray his word" and "peet the law".
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end as quickly as possible the institutional and political crisis, by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of regaining popular and democratic legitimacy while protest is raging throughout the country.
Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote favorably, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Especially since this recourse to a hasty vote is due to the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I keep the full powers", these are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, with a large Islamist majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals missed the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, believing that they had not been able to assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society had done the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 substitute members were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, it is most often unanimously that the articles were voted on.
Some commentators were amused by the fact that one of the only differences of the day was expressed around... the hour of prayer, some members of the committee believing that the pendulum of the constituent was badly settled.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, has 234 articles.
The object of all attention, Article 2 finally remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major claim, hoped to be able to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed a stricter application.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their good will and their respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy,” respond the liberals, who see it only as a communication stunt.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They include article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, particularly in terms of verifying the compliance of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the beginnings of a theocracy.”
The fears of the Liberals are further stoked by the fact that the next president of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"At the moment, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulamas but academics, for some trained in the French system" tempers Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms used borrow from religious vocabulary.
It refers to "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ed].
And the question may arise in the future as to the extent to which civilian judges are competent to rule on it.”
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extended powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced in comparison to what they were under the old regime.
Another contentious point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will trials of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as human rights groups have called for.
The latter also express their concerns about the text, which they consider liberticide.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, including the press.
In addition, there are no more articles that echo the protection of women, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak last night on television, demonstrations are scheduled this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the center of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and wilderness.
Argoumenty i Fakty has chosen five main reasons to visit Israel.
Go and worship the holy places
A must-see: the banks of the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who penetrates these "baptismal funds" will be touched by Divine Grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was changed into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm or where the fishing was miraculous.
It was there that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk along the Street of Suffering or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the Antonia fortress (the praetorium), where the trial was held, then led by the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of the Unction and the burial.
This is where the Christian center of the world is, symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest place of the Jews: the Wailing Wall which constitutes the rest of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave small words with prayers that are then answered.
Travel at a height
Visit the ruins of the Masada fortress, an ancient refuge from enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins are found on the steep rocks of a mountain at 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can go there on their own.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont which welcomes many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
The old beliefs are that pagan gods once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
Impossible to visit them all during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth a visit.
First: The Israel Museum located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the very old Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
See also: Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
It mainly exhibits the paintings of the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of casts of visitors and supervisors of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the unique private Ralli Museum where you can admire Rodin’s sculptures.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which looks back at the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the Children’s Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter into total darkness.
Stars are shimmering.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
Israel’s three major resorts lie on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, because the temperature of the water does not drop below 21 ° while that of the air can reach 23 °.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point of the Earth, 417 m below sea level.
The azure water contains brine and very easily retains bathers, even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes that surround it are of surreal beauty.
They come to perform a treatment based on salt water, silt, curative sludge and to treat different diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of Antiquity
They are guarded by Tel Aviv’s old town, Jaffa, on the edge of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris which connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life.
Tourists especially like to walk through the narrow alleys that bear the name of the zodiac signs.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds who have come to do photo shoots of all Israel and even other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk in the Roman theater, "conquer" the fortress of the crusaders.
During the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer the dollars to the euro, because they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
As for urban transport, it is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and able to connect the lower and upper parts of the city.
It is almost an underground funicular.
The journey in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, Jewish tradition wants to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturdays.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturdays, markets, shops and public transport cease their activity.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels only serve kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes made up of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish dough, different sauces, balls of ground chickpeas, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats that walk the haughty air.
You can see them at night sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
These cats love passing places and do not refuse to be regaled.
Car rental varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24h (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Entrance to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
Three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel in 2012.
They were mainly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118,8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
"Who has a language in Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
While MPs and human rights activists are debating what the law on compulsory language testing will give, fraudsters selling “false” certificates have already appeared in the country
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are nationals of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to earn money to help their families who have stayed at home.
Since 1 December, a law has been in force that stipulates that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian exam.
For the time being, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, in time, promises the Federal Migration Service, the tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also that of the History of Russia and the foundations of law.
You will have to validate your language skills in Russian to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has official language status are exempt.
Persons who obtained educational certificates or diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not covered by this law.
Benefits, Negative Attitudes and Protection of Rights
The network of examination centers will be under the auspices of Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, University of Friendship of Peoples, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other higher education institutions of Russia.
Immigrants will be able to take exams in all cities of the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened throughout the country.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what is it going to do?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, say the representatives of the migration service, it will reduce the number of people suffering from "slavery at work".
Many speak of defending the rights of migrant workers, says Victor Sebelev, director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan.
Protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without the understanding of the language, says Sebelev, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "journey" in an overcrowded cottage where he and dozens of his fellows will torment each other for months without food and paper and will have to work between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"At home, they are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are deceived, they take their passports, and they do not receive the expected salary," confirms the Head of the Directorate of Migration Services for the work of the Migration Service of Tajikistan, Tolib Charipov.
Don't argue with me, Mr. Policeman!
However, many citizens of Central Asian republics who wish to come and earn money in Russia say that they not only do not know the language of the country they wish to visit, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is not their fault, of course, but their misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford even a fair primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have enough to feed their children, let alone dress them properly and equip them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people leave to earn money as soon as the opportunity arises.
It’s hard when you don’t know the language, they say.
“You feel diminished and diminished.”
Human rights defenders, however, note an important aspect of the language law.
The exams will be intended only for migrants who have a legal status.
Without status, there will be no formal examination or work thereafter.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbid to come in"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and always these language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 thousand rubles.
And then, one can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we do not have registration, hence the cases of extortion.
“They ask us for 100, 200 rubles, enough to buy cigarettes, tea,” said Umed Khushkadamov, a national of Tajikistan.
“Make quick, do not skimp and buy yourself a beautiful work of art.”
From the first day the Language Act came into force, it was discovered that it was not only the migrants' registration papers that were found to be false.
Several false language examination certificates have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
Falsified papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not have them for nothing: each migrant who hoped to facilitate himself the task of the examinations had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Government officials and human rights advocates agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these “paper ends.”
The authorities can give migrant workers who have not been able to validate the examination at the first glance time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market.
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is proposing to tighten the law against civilian weapon bearers.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: from the shooting at weddings to the killing of seven people by Moscow jurist Dmitry Vinogradov.
The police want to ban the wearing of rubber bullets in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining a gun license from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee for Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the Arms Act would be introduced in the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is happy to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "squeezing the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demand to abandon "this insane hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasiliy Lesnikov, a BBC lawyer and crime specialist, told the Russian service.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, over a period of six months in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services while 1.168 thousand crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are certain that strengthening civil weapons laws will not prevent criminals from sourcing from the black market.
According to them, one can find today in Moscow any weapon for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior says it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black market for weapons is supplied through several channels.
There are five main canals, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served for ten years at the Ministry of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot from a site taking orders from weapons
The first is the "military trace", i.e. the weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
“These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by Caucasians,” Baranets said.
The second type of weapons from the black market are those stolen by criminals from law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stocks and those stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal pistols go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of these have often suffered explosions.
"Attested versions indicate that some fires were deliberately started to conceal the deficit," the former military official said.
For Baranets, weapons manufacturers have something to do with it.
"We see private weapons factories that do not compete with competition on the international market and sell weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow," said an expert.
Another source of the black market is smuggling.
A significant proportion of pistols and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply," adds the former soldier.
Where do the weapons come from?
Experts have estimated the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on this issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Studies for Public Administration.
Specialists analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminal files and public data from weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the military and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons on the black market were found there "because of employees whose work is related to weapons," the report said.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from places of military conflict, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% are from “clandestine searches”.
A seller and consultant at an armory who asked to remain anonymous says that for a long time no one buys the weapons found by these clandestine search specialists; they are too old.
Most often, according to him, the sellers will look for the new goods in the military warehouses.
The person buys through a sign a unit, for example a TT gun.
It is delivered by passing the goods through a wire mesh.
"He transports it to town and sells it for $900 per unit with two chargers," he said.
“It’s true that the police are aware of all the cases, so when crimes are about to be elucidated, they make a check purchase from illegal arms dealers,” he added.
" Like in a luxury boutique "
The seller and the buyer are usually found through acquaintances.
I looked at sites, blogs, until a guy showed up and offered to come to Begovaya station where someone was going to take me to a "corner" to haggle.
The price of the gun, I was given it on the spot
Victor Baranets as Military Observer
To find a gun, I need to know someone who has a contact, says the salesman. I know someone, but I don't trust him.
There are vendors in the markets, but there you also have to come by saying for example "From such a person, who asked me to convey that his daughter has lost a tooth".
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with the help of someone I trust.
He only delivers them to me because he knows I won’t give it to him.
Newbies are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former militaryman Victor Baranets tried his hand as a buyer of illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
The patterns, according to him, have not changed.
He was given a photo album in which there was "anything we want".
“I thought I was in a luxury shop,” the soldier recalled.
There is no secret to the buyer, Baranets explains, you can try anything.
As a potential customer, I don't just buy, we go with the seller in the forest and we set up a target.
“I’m allowed to shoot and when I’m convinced that the weapon is working well, we start negotiating,” the expert said.
A shop from his couch
Search engines display sites and groups on Vkontakte where you can buy weapons "for different uses".
For this, we do not need any documents and no one to meet.
“You just have to have a precise amount of money,” the company said in an advertisement on its website, “Buy a gun or a combat machine gun.”
Users leave their request and ask their questions.
And we sell to the miners?
"Without permission, of course," asks the user "Ivan" (spelling preserved).
