Nearly a quarter of U.S. teens go through a cashier job at McDonald's
In recent days, a wave of protests has mounted against the low wages practiced by Walmart supermarkets and famous fast food chains such as McDonald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
At the moment, no one can predict whether this wave will grow or run out of steam quickly.
These actions are supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing associations.
Along with the modest wage increases for basic workers at Walmart and in fast-food chains, the organizers of the protests want unions to be created.
This sector is not currently covered by the trade union movement.
46 cents a year?
Protests began last week, after Thanksgiving, the "Black Friday," as a pouring rain of sales took hold of millions of people across America and sometimes triggered glare.
On that day, some employees of the company Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left their jobs to organize pickets with unions and left-wing activists in the company’s stores whose products are aimed at consumers in the modest and middle classes.
Walmart markets everything from diapers to shotguns to car batteries, vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
Products are on average 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many low-paid Walmart employees shop only at their workplace.
The price and choice of products have made Walmart one of the most powerful groups in the United States.
According to critics, Walmart can afford to sell its products cheaply, especially because of the low salaries of its employees.
They also complain about difficult working conditions, such as the lack of forklifts or portable scanners.
Participants in the "Black Friday" protests demanded a pay rise, they complained that the price of medical insurance provided by the company had increased from $30 to $100 a month.
For the basic Walmart employee who earns $9.5 an hour, that’s a sum he can’t afford.
Scientists at California’s Berkley University show that if Walmart raised the average wage to $12 an hour, it would cost the group $3.2 billion.
That’s 1.1% more than he currently spends.
If Walmart were to shift all the wage increases onto the shoulders of consumers, every run in the store would cost them 46 cents more.
They will spend only $12.39 more in a year than they do now.
Supporters of Walmart note with satisfaction that the protests took place in only nine states and did no harm to the group.
The "Black Friday" continued in stores from 8:00 in the evening to midnight the next day and Walmart sold over this period 5,000 items per second.
Its caisses have completed a total of 100 million transactions for the "Black Friday".
Company spokesman Dan Fogleman said in an interview with the left-wing Huffington Post that a total of "less than five" Walmart employees had left their jobs and that the protest was just a "com operation among many" on the part of the organizing union.
"Next customer!"
Protests continued this week in New York and were no longer about Walmart stores (in this progressive city, they are not much appreciated, which is why they are not yet established there) but McDonald's and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald’s advertises selling billions of servings and then they don’t even give you sick leave and don’t pay you for the work you’ve done honestly!
Jumaane Williams, Member of the New York City Council
Currently, the minimum wage under federal and New York law is $7.25 per hour.
Fast foods increase them over time, but on average, its core employees earn $8.90 an hour in New York City.
No one touches less than them in this city.
It's inconceivable for me to live with that money in New York.
There was a time when almost a quarter of American teenagers worked at McDonald's after high school while living with their parents.
Few people saw it as their main source of income or wanted to stay there for a long time.
Today, I find myself interviewing McDonald's employees who complain about having to live with that salary and sometimes having to feed their children with it.
On the other hand, on the Wall Street Journal forum there are comments saying that it is irresponsible to make children if you do not know what you are going to feed them with.
Protesters who launched the movement Thursday at 6:30 a.m. near McDonald’s on 40th Street and Madison Avenue demanded that fast food cashiers and cooks be paid at least $15 an hour, a multiplication of more than twice the current minimum wage.
They also called for the establishment of trade unions in the fast food sector.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from obstructing and punishing union protesters with harassment or dismissal.
However, administration rarely simplifies their lives.
For a union, grabbing fast food remains a difficult task, and that, for concrete reasons.
One of the main ones is the extraordinary staff turnover.
They don't agree
Other tumultuous demonstrations were held near several other fast food chains.
The highlight of the protest was the mid-day rally near McDonald’s in Times Square with the intervention of several local Democratic politicians, including City Council member Jumaane Williams, who said: “McDonald’s advertises selling billions of servings and after they don’t even give you sick leave and don’t pay you for the work you did honestly!”
The protesters were supported by other prominent New York Democrats, including Mayor Bill De Blasio, who said, “We all need to support fast food workers to get the fair pay and economic well-being that every New Yorker deserves.
The New York Times described the event as the largest in the fast food industry in its history.
But only a few hundred people participated, not to mention that not all of them were fast food workers, who employ tens of thousands of people in New York.
It is difficult to say at the moment whether this spark of mass movement will make small.
"At the moment, we can only moderately fool the brain"
Lately, fans of new technologies have become accustomed to perceiving augmented reality through special glasses.
Initially, it was Google that unveiled its current model this summer at its annual conference and in November it was revealed that Microsoft had applied for the patent.
However, it is clear from the interview with the director of the 3D interactive technologies group of the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge, Shahram Izadi, that for the scientists of this company, the glasses are already ancient history.
They are tempted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands, by creating open virtual spaces.
- Could you tell us in a few words what your research group is doing?
- We are working on the interaction between man and machine and at the same time we are trying to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
Humanity as a whole has remained for the moment with pixels on a flat screen and sometimes with touch.
We want to look 5 to 10 years ahead and guess the radical changes that will occur with this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and almost no Xbox today sells without Kinect because everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What does the future hold for us?
- Although the Kinect made the physical interaction, a lot of things happen on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
Information capture has been improved (the system receives more data), but performance, for now, not really.
We’re trying to change that and we’re working on truly 3D imaging systems that run on different technologies, including projection technologies.
It is necessary to bring the computer world out into ours, into the physical world, to make it more tactile.
For this, however, it is necessary to identify not only the user, but also the space that surrounds it.
In this way, we will be able to complement the real world with virtual objects in a more practical form.
And for starters, let’s get rid of these stupid virtual reality headsets!
- What do you think of the voice command?
It’s appreciated, but isn’t it overrated?
One cannot say that this is the panacea: the question of confidentiality arises because one does not always want to inform others of one's actions or intentions.
In fact, each type of interaction with the computer is good, but each in its niche.
For example, to control the devices in public places, we had a project for which we thought of gestures, not broad gestures, but rather discrete, restricted gestures.
The gestures were not captured by the camera of the device, but by a hand-worn bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is currently large, but it is theoretically possible to reduce it to the size of a watch.
In fact, the future will be marked by the mixed command, for example: gesture + voice.
- What do you mean?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass you this can?
You would do it with words and gestures.
- I usually only talk.
- Oh, it's going to be hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt based on what the machine may or may not be doing at some point?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual rapprochement.
I think that very soon we will have to work on developing new types of sensors that will allow us to better identify the reactions of humans.
This can be laser sensors, for example, and they produce a fairly good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- If we're interested in your work on Xbox Kinect sensors, what don't you like about modern cameras?
Do they lack resolution, depth, or anything else?
- In principle, it is on the current generation that we base our work on 3D recognition.
It would obviously be nice to get about 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 c/s.
But the problem is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
Compared to this last point, all current technologies are pretty good, it adds work to algorithm designers.
We must keep in mind the resolution along the X and Y axes, but also Z.
Speed also matters a lot, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and 30 c/s is really not enough, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our Redmond laboratory, gave the touch of the sensors a regular processing delay of between 1 and 100 seconds, with the current sensors being closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands how much this influences the interaction of man and machine.
I would need a device of this type in my work, but not needing to touch, to have more frames per second.
Shouldn’t we increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second, a receiver of the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually a usual sensor of the visible field.
It is not used to define the depth of the object.
A lot of cameras could solve this problem.
Or make it worse by increasing the required volume of calculations.
It would be interesting to create a flexible product similar to the Kinect, play with the curve of the cameras and see how it could help define the locations.
As far as I can remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that from the point of view of the daily use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the platforms with the most perspectives?
- Of course, walking all the time with a smartphone with your hands up is not practical but here's what I think: the best option would be a "transient" augmented reality that would allow you from a cloud platform to switch from glasses to smartphones.
Glasses are a very personal device and this is what makes their strength (the personal elements are the ones you are the only one to see) and at the same time their weakness: augmented reality from the glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects in collaboration with other people.
Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is no longer accessible only to Tony Stark in Iron Man but also to the mere mortal.
There is a problem to which the opponents of this idea point the finger: there is no tactile sensation!
The hands feel nothing.
What answers does your group prepare for this challenge?
In my classes, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth could very well be the addition of tactile sensations.
At the moment, one of the interesting techniques is the use of the second hand to serve as an image medium.
It perfectly records the pressures!
But there are also technologies that are really intended to attribute palpability to these "images in the air": for example the interference of several ultrasound rays directed towards a specific point where the finger is located and which gives you the sensation, for the moment still weak, of a breath of air on the tips of the fingers.
There are also wristbands worn on the wrists that affect the nerve endings of the fingers, they are also a work axis with perspectives.
- And you tried to fool the brain?
Make him think that he feels what he should normally feel when he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
There’s still a task down there that’s going to take a long time: how to make someone who’s physically in a very small space believe they’re walking in an almost infinite open space – we’re working on the concepts of treadmills (nothing to do with those found in fitness clubs), mobile platforms and also giant balls.
At the moment, we can only moderately deceive the brain, there are still many years of work.
This is what makes the work on virtual reality so interesting for the researcher: many things are still in the absolute state of fertilization.
