Giving birth in space
The Earth is in danger.
Global warming or collision with a deadly asteroid.
Space shuttle caravans with earthlings on board set off in search of a rescue planet.
To save humanity, a big question arises: how to keep our species alive in weightlessness or on a rescue planet?
I don't think there's much to choose from.
There are actually two real planets that can be conquered, if only by hypothesis.
“It’s about Venus and Mars,” says Vladimir Sourdine, a researcher at the P.K. Chternberg State Astronomical Institute (GAICh).
If conditions on Mars are more suitable for life, the temperature on the surface of Venus is 500.
You can only live at very high altitudes or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
We began to focus on the issues of reproduction in space by focusing on the flora.
Half a century ago, experiments were carried out on plants.
Four generations of small peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from terrestrial varieties.
Then, insects, small breeding Drosophila flies, were put into orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to see how an embryo grew in weightlessness.
At the exit, we get a perfectly normal chick.
Then the problems begin.
"The problem is that the chick has to find a support, it has to get on its feet and start moving," explains the director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP) Vladimir Sychev.
By finding no support, the chicks were agitated in a disorderly manner.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophy.
The chicks did not react to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die after four days.
"We widened their eyes twice, then gave up, because it's simply impossible to work with them there," says Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of the experiment with chicks in space.
The last biological "miniature ark" with animals was sent into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, the biosatellite "Bion" will only carry species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetuses into space.
In principle, nothing supernatural has been discovered.
"It was still about biosatellites and then it's the only experiment. You have to do this kind of research," says Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats gave birth to their offspring.
However, it is not yet possible to make reproductions directly in space.
It's no small matter.
By losing their usual environment, animals are no longer able to realize their sexual instincts.
Unlike animals, humans are capable of doing this.
Homo sapiens possess abstract thought, it is able to create a suitable emotional background.
This type of experience is not done for ethical reasons.
But women have been in space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was taken by Tereshkova.
And the female organism is the most precious thing humanity has.
Our seagull flew away and no one on Earth could tell if it would hold up after a flight into space.
If she could have given birth to a child after the theft.
“Nobody was answering that question,” says Vakhtang Vatchnadzé, a retired rocket and space worker.
In June 1964, just a year after her flight into space, the first female cosmonaut Valentina Tereshkova gave birth to a baby girl.
The child’s father, Andrian Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman cosmonaut Svetlana Savitskaya, after having been in orbit twice and even working in an extra-vehicular environment, gave birth to a son.
However, the risk persists.
We have few, even very few cosmonauts who have had nothing and who give birth to a healthy offspring after long flights.
"And if they are longer, it presents a danger even during flights in orbit," concludes the pilot and cosmonaut, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of Russia, Valeriy Poliakov.
Yet humanity must seek new solutions in biotechnology, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravitation.
Hydrology laboratory of the Cosmonauts Preparation Center: mandatory stage of flight preparation.
Here, in zero buoyancy, cosmonauts train at extra-vehicular exits.
Water imitates weightlessness.
If for adults, water is comfortable but yet a foreign environment, for infants, this is their true element.
Small amphibious men seem to confirm this: life on Earth comes from the ocean.
Since the baby develops about 9 months in the lymphatic fluid of his mother's belly, it is easier for him to get used to the water.
This is in principle logical, because from his birth to his first bath, it takes only 2 weeks.
“It’s very little to forget,” explains infant swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
In a word, if weightlessness is a more natural state for the newly born child, the woman needs gravitation, weight force.
In weightlessness, the muscles of the belly, the pelvis atrophy very quickly, the ability to push the baby is lost.
Okay, let's ignore that by relying on birth simulators.
We can of course prepare a delivery in a special room, the woman will manage to get him out.
"And then?" asked Poliakov, inviting him to reflect on this complex question.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravitation.
If it does not feel the Earth's attraction, the body does not form the skeleton or the muscular system.
One cannot dress an infant as an adult with a special suit for training.
He will simply be deprived of his vital needs.
"And this experience that we would consider in this case imagining the birth of a child in a foreign environment will result in the return to Earth of a disabled child, completely disadapted," predicts the Director of the Committee for Bioethics of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences, Igor Pestov.
The birth of children in space is still a theory.
However, over time this will become a reality, as the Earthlings travel in their shuttles to a distant planet that will become the home of their space-born offspring.
The head of the ISC (Higher Institution for the Control of Public Finances) said: "The control of pseudo-self-employment (in Czech 'varc system') has failed because of the politicians.
In the field of public procurement, the Czech Republic has competent inspectors and quality legislation, but it lags behind in its implementation.
Miloslav Kala, the vice-president of the Supreme Audit Institution, said in an interview with Aktuln.cz.
“The law will never be perfect, but its enforcement must be fair and, in my opinion, that is what is lacking with us,” Kala said in her commentary on the current situation.
A joint inspection by Czech and German inspectors also suggests similar conclusions.
He cites as an example of abusive practice the approach of the "varc system" by Petr Nesas.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not annoy contractors with controls, so is it allowed or prohibited?
“The law has to be enforced one way or another, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government can’t stop an authority from going to inspect to demand compliance with the law,” Kala said.
At the meeting of the Supervisory Committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you referred to a Czech-German project in which the public procurement laws of these two countries were compared.
What was it really about?
This is a parallel check that we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation provides for how to manage public procurement and specific national legislation, as well as a practice proper, follow it.
We have collected all this and although this control procedure is not yet completed, very interesting differences have appeared to us: generally speaking, our legislation is perhaps "more severe and of better quality", nevertheless, according to certain parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms, therefore, that it is not enough to draw up ever more detailed rules, but that it is necessary to devote ourselves to the implementation of the law itself.
How can this project concretely help you and what does it mean for you?
This kind of joint monitoring should help us stop trying to clarify the laws, to lower and improve the thresholds, when it does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means obtaining the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But lowering market thresholds will not necessarily achieve this goal.
It could be that this system is so overwhelmed by paperwork that those who seek the loopholes will find many more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You are talking about internal problems regarding the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an institution similar to our SAI or a different mode of organization?
As for the institutions, similarly to the ISC, the Bundesrechnungshof operates there which is organized similarly, it also has a council constituted a little differently, but these two institutions proceed basically in a similar way.
The competences are also, to a certain extent, similar, but with a certain nuance in relation to our system: Germany is a federal structure, so it also has accounts of this type at the level of the various Lands.
HRB can only control federal money, which is the same as government resources.
The public funds managed by the regions and the municipalities are controlled there at the level of the courts of account of the Land.
As far as national legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, but in some areas Germany is often referred to as a model, but surely it cannot be said to do better in all areas.
Maybe it's because they have better inspectors?
No, certainly not, but I repeat, I do not have comparison data.
However, it must also be said that this country, which we consider to be a model, also faces a whole series of problems.
Otherwise they would have no advantage in cooperating with our institution, right?
As far as national legislation is concerned, what has the amendment of the Public Procurement Act meant for you as an institution?
As this amendment has entered into force relatively recently, it has not yet had an impact on our control operations.
As we carry out post-clearance checks, we have to deal with a certain delay.
Our observations concern only, for the moment, the process of preparation of future controls - we have launched a new instrument of "detection of risks of mismanagement" with which we have screened nearly 14,000 public contracts - there these changes will of course be felt, because the thresholds have been modified as well as the conditions of certain types of tendering procedures and so on.
Do you consider the adoption of this law rather as an advantage or as an additional burden for the administration?
I believe this legislation is a step in the right direction and I hope that the future will confirm it.
The problem that can arise is that these rules become more severe and it is not possible to respect them.
Already under the previous regulation, the provider (e.g. the regional council, in the case of regional operational programmes) forced the subjects under control to accept that any breach of the contract law meant a breach of budgetary discipline.
So is it really worth making the law more severe in this way?
No, not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack the system or abuse it but not punish those who make formal mistakes without consequence on the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on the administration.
So what is the solution to get out of it?
Let's look where we're not going.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS was not going to annoy entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called “varc” system – what does that mean?
