Your international projects are minimalist, so far you have played for example in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage the organization and logistics of your tours?
It's not as bad as it sounds at first.
We have five members in an electric wheelchair whose gear must travel in the hold, naturally we also trim a lot of luggage and instrument boxes....
So far everything has been more or less always going well, the British Airways were always perfectly prepared for us, they surprised me more than once.
Even in Moscow, from where we returned recently, everything went smoothly.
Through your travels abroad, you can compare how these countries differ in terms of accessibility for people with reduced mobility, public opinion attitude towards people with disabilities and so on.
What have been your experiences so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than at home, we have just witnessed in Moscow that in the east all are still in an initial phase.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is still very inaccessible to people with disabilities; there, it is not yet common for a person to travel alone in an electric wheelchair in the center of the city.
They do not yet consider it obvious to give priority to a person in a wheelchair in an elevator.
Fortunately, there too, an association trying to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities is being created.
How do we still have to catch up with more developed countries?
There are a lot of things we are still late for...
It is important to mention that improvements and refinements always depend on the efforts of the people concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with a heavy disability to travel alone in public spaces; they can go to the toilet, to the museum, anywhere...
It is still not very common there that a large number of people with disabilities actively participate in social life, on this point, you, The Tap Tap, are rather at the forefront of progress!
Respect for the public and easy access is one thing, but the situation will really start to change when we have famous sportsmen, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers among us.
At the moment, these are just isolated cases of people with a strong will.
