The movie Argo: when everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protesters made up of Islamist students stormed the US embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome, it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously undermined the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to secure the release of the hostages.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, a blow further aggravated later by the fiasco of the attempt to liberate the hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iran sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle contributed greatly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory to America.
Just before it was occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated events, they found themselves in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran thanks to a fantastic cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a film crew who came to scout for the filming of a big science fiction show.
Combination of genders
Exfiltration expert Tony Mendez's plan required Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized magazines reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictitious production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
On the one hand, it is a realistically conceived political thriller but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful coup, a treachery - as, for example, in the trilogy Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirty.
The atmospheres follow one another: documentary-style Tehran sequences (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations were transcribed in the film, there are no big differences),
lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the hallways and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his acting ceased to elicit ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark policeman "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It’s also Affleck’s first film that doesn’t take place in his hometown of Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed his first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where Tehran’s role is “held” by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real events; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clarity that also suggests the confusion and unpredictability occurring when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the fake film crew in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to settle for a subject that actually offered few thrilling scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
He does very well, he sometimes adds some elements to the reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is dismissed by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the airstrip are pretty far-fetched).
Argo's weakness lies in its dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
While it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood cooperators, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are not, far from it, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, he lets himself be seen with moderate interest, appreciating the direction and retro style of the 70s.
It draws the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story still, in a way, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated nature of the representation of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, it does the trick.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and the circus
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which conducts a public inquiry every year on the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to launch the contest of the regulation or ideas from the most absurd "EU workshop".
“The fact that the EU is considering, in recent times, adopting a quota of 40 percent of women for the management of large European companies was at the origin of our decision,” said Patrik Nacher, the organiser of the survey.
Among the absurdities mentioned, there is already, for example, the recent decision of the European Court to unify insurance premiums for men and women.
Until now, however, women have benefited from life insurance rates because they represent, objectively, a lower risk for insurance companies.
People can report until the end of the year any other such incredible idea of the "EU workshop".
“The vote will take place before the end of February 2013,” Nacher said.
Controversial EU regulations include, for example, the obligation to add organic components to fuels, which has harmful consequences for the environment, or the ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers, only because they contain a relatively small amount of a dangerous substance, or the hen cage size directive, which has led to higher egg prices.
Criticisms have also been made in the past of the de facto ban on the use of the term "butter spread" or the withdrawal of the sale of conventional bulbs.
Quality bananas should be 14 centimetres in size.
The European administration often reacts under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby whose demands are usually defended in Brussels by a state or a group of states (for example, the Czech Republic currently imposes the demands of its banks by threatening to use its veto power).
The interests of pressure groups are also, for example, at the root of the fact that in the Union bananas must not be less than 14 cm in size or have an "abnormal curve".
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it was only harmonising non-homogeneous national standards that complicated trade.
Fruit and vegetable standards have been relaxed despite opposition from some states, claiming that existing guidelines result in food wastage.
The first prize may be awarded in this survey to last year’s EU regulation that requires inflatable balloons to carry a warning that children under the age of 8 should not inflate unsupervised by adults.
The EU referred to a U.S. survey that found balloons were the leading cause of child choking deaths among toys.
A similar restriction applies to children under the age of 14 when it comes to blowing in fair trumpets.
At home, too, we have weird ideas.
The following rule concerning European officials themselves is quite absurd: because of the sensitivity of this theme for Greece, anyone with an official function within the EU cannot use the name "Macedonia" and must, instead, speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslavia Republic of Macedonia).
In collaboration with the "Laissez Faire" association of liberal economists, the Bankovn server named in this survey, in addition to some of the absurdities mentioned above, the EU regulation on the volume of food reserves in the territory of the Czech Republic.
The EU had set maximum volumes for food reserves that could be found in the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the volumes set for canned mushrooms and thus risked a heavy fine.
The organizers of this survey found it interesting to pay money to certain countries because they do not have access to the sea and the idea of granting a subsidy to apply for subsidies.
However, these ideas do not come from Brussels but from Prague.
“The fact that we don’t have a sea handicaps us.
We are going to ask the European Union for a refund," said then-Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (SSD) in the autumn of 2004.
He argued that, as a result of our wheat production, and following the so-called interventionist purchases, the state had found itself with full stocks that it had to export.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us millions of euros, because the Czech Republic is far from the ports.
In the end, the European Commission responded positively to Czech demand and organised a call for tenders for the purchase of wheat from countries without maritime access.
The grants for obtaining grants were proposed to the municipalities by the Ministry of Local Development headed by Minister Pavel Nemec (US-DEU), which was to be used, in concrete terms, to draft applications for grants granted by Brussels.
The EU says: "Bizarre regulations are rare".
While regulations often attract criticism in Member States, according to many experts, the EU's efforts to regulate and improve the effectiveness of the Union's functioning and in the field of its overall development are rather worthy of praise.
More serious is, for example, according to experts, the problem of the use of EU subsidies for projects that have absolutely nothing to do with the strengthening of European integration, but which were imposed by the Member States during the budgetary negotiations.
The fact that the Czech Republic, like other countries of the Union, has to fight in Brussels for the right to use specific names for these traditional products (a struggle from which it does not always win) arouses strong emotions among the Czechs.
If after six years of battle against the Germans and Austrians, the Czechs successfully defended the name "Olomoucké tvaruky", as for the name "Tuzemska rum" which dates back to our home in the 19th century, our producers had to replace it with the name "Tuzemak".
Only products based on cane sugar alcohol, and not on beet sugar, may bear the name rum.
In the official EU list of registered products, you can find today in the company of world-famous cheeses such as Feta or Gorgonzola, the marzipan of Lubeck or Parma ham, the biscuits of Karlovy Vary ("Karlovarské suchary"), the carp of Pohoiselice and of Tueboe ("Pohoiselicka a Tueboesk").
Gingerbread from Pardubice ("Pardubick" pernak) and cakes called "Cornets de Hosice" ("Hosické trubiky") can also be proud of their community brand.
People want me to save the Republic, but I'm just an amateur, says Senator Okamura
Mr. Senator, how do we get the idea of running for president?
It’s not about being a senator or a president that matters to me.
If everything worked without problems in our country, I would not be a candidate anywhere.
But I can no longer bear to see how the country has been looted for the last twenty years, that thieves are not locked up and taxes and the age of retirement are rising.
I had no ambition to become a politician.
But when I see something that I don't like, then I try to find a way to change it.
And since I am over forty years old and I am independent, a member of no party, I have no other solution to influence the situation than to run in presidential or senatorial elections.
You entered the Senate but you quickly set out for the Castle.
Aren’t you turning your back on those who elected you?
I've always said that I'll get into the battle for the Castle based on the results of the Senate election.
Later, I made it clear that if I were elected a senator, I would run for president.
My goal is not the function, it is only an instrument allowing me to realize my vision.
That is why I need the greatest influence and the broadest mandate.
The problem is not only that as a nation we grumble at the bar or in front of our television set, but also that we trample on those who try to bring about change.
Added to this is the press that breaks the reputation of people and confuses freedom of speech with freedom to lie.
For example, it has been said about me that I bribe journalists or that I have been the adviser to Jia Parubek.
Let's get to your visions.
You started the fight for the Castle with the themes of material and criminal liability of politicians and retroactive tax declarations beyond twenty million [of CZK].
To that end, you must change the law.
As president, you do not have such power and only the Senate as a whole can propose laws.
How do you want to solve this problem?
When I, as a citizen, lobbied for tour guide activities to be a liberal profession, I won my case.
The problem is politics: when someone comes from the left or the right with a good project, it is knowingly refused and it delays the citizens.
As an independent member of no party, I am much more likely to get the support of all parliamentary parties.
I have the advantage of being able, without categorization and partisan dogma, to take from each side what is best for our country and implement it.
Do you think of yourself as a right-winger or a left-winger?
From a Czech point of view, I feel like people are putting me rather to the left.
For me, whether it’s a little bit left or right, it’s not really important.
For me, the important thing is that we move forward.
What matters to me is not that people are left-wing or right-wing but to bring people together.
I always support any solution that contributes to the common good, even if it is proposed by the Communist Party or ODS, and I also act impartially against bad ideas.
Are you angry when someone says you are a populist?
But does not what you said prove it?
When you develop a business plan in a company, you also have a certain optimal goal and vision.
You're trying to get closer.
Some may call it populism, but all the proposals I’m talking about have been implemented by the world and recognized experts have been talking about it.
But without the support of the parliament, you only have slogans left.
You won’t survive long in politics with this.
Do you think that if you go to people and talk to them, you will succeed, for example, in imposing material and criminal responsibility?
I have no other option.
I must convince politicians, journalists and public opinion and try to rally them to my side in order to impose it.
If I were elected president, it would not be a problem to broadcast live on television my request to the presidents of the parliamentary parties to legislate on the material and criminal responsibility of politicians, civil servants, judges and prosecutors.
They should then eventually explain why they don't want it.
When there is a strong personality who will identify the abuse, it will be possible to put pressure on the political scene.
Take for example the election of the president by direct suffrage, it was obtained through the pressure of public opinion.
I admit, without hesitation, to be an amateur, not a genius or an intellectual.
I try to find allies for my opinions and visions.
I just got into politics and I'm trying to get the majority support for my program.
I'm trying, alone, to get things done, and if it doesn't work, I'll stop in six years and go back to the private sector.
It’s a bit like Okamura having to save the Czech Republic.
I'm not a savior.
I know that only one person can make a difference, which is why I went to a number of personalities to ask them to run for the Senate elections as well.
I met Radim Janaura, but he refused because of the amount of work.
I have at least supported investigative journalist Jana Lorencova who exposed the fuel oil frauds.
I introduced myself because people are really unhappy but now I hesitate.
Sixty percent of the people did not vote and what did, for the most part, gave their vote to a representative of the establishment.
In the Senate, we are just two independents.
People have elected a Senate that can hardly impose changes.
Nevertheless, I will fight for my vision, for example the direct election of mayors and prefects of regions.
Are you planning to start your own party?
No, not yet, because I don't have time to check if every potential member's past is spotless and then I don't have the financial means.
I also have no money for my presidential campaign, I only have twenty thousand in my "transparent" account.
You don't have any money?
You’re talking about tax returns, what’s yours?
I estimate the value of my personal property at about 60 million.
I have in Prague a plot of land worth 25 million, an apartment worth ten million, another apartment worth 8 million, a collection of works of art worth about ten million, an Aston Martin worth 3.5 million and a Skoda Superb worth 1 million and a few million in my account.
By the way, I own an Aston Martin, because it was a kid’s dream: I’ve always loved James Bond, who drove, was gallant with women and fought against evil and abuse.
You drive an Aston Martin, you have a $60 million estate and you don't have any money for your campaign?
You want to change the Republic but you don’t want to invest your own money in it?
It's not very convincing.
I don't have $15 million for this campaign.
Should I go into debt?
I've already invested $2.5 million in the campaign.
The fact that I do not have a sponsor shows that my program does not arouse much interest.
I don't have to pay for this campaign out of my own pocket.
My campaign expenses are generally covered by the compensation I will receive as a senator.
But I couldn't afford it, like paying for my son's English school, which costs 30 thousand a month.
If my only goal was to make money, I would not run for office.
So you will continue your commercial activities to be able to live?
Didn't you say you'd mute your activities?
But this is not related to the amount of this remuneration.
As I promised, I partially curtailed my activities.
For example, my assistant will take over the management of the travel agency in the spring.
People want me to be a Samaritan who saves the Republic.
But I have to live on something.
What was your usual monthly salary when you were an entrepreneur?
I was winning and I continue to win between two hundred and four hundred thousand.
If I were president, I would end my business.
