Architects at MVRDV prove that true adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To be convinced, just look at Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it's very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a nearby large company, tells us: "Yes, it is indeed beautiful, this building".
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one goes willingly to one of these rinsing libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeper town that has nothing attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The 80,000-strong municipality has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore a few neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro notes in the form of pretty miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to regain control of the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, from the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of witty and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and entered the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a sneer on his face.
And while the jury members were still looking at each other, bewildered and shrugging their shoulders, Maas, the cheeky, piled up his choice books in order of size to make a pyramid, and ended his speech backed up by activist arguments with a: "common dear!"
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain of 30 million euros has sprung from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and some buildings and terraced houses for a total of 50 homes.
In early November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This is how this small, dull town, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and a town hall with a bewildering ugliness, whose white facades invite us to think that they are home to a dairy, has been enriched by a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under a cheese bell.
Certainly, an elevator transports you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you tread the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The entirely glass interior is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant street lights speak unequivocally the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public benches, dogs and little boys and girls who play ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally the library shelves are along the facade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal,” Maas says.
We completely upset the classic spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been skillfully arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes panelling, sometimes balustrades, sometimes stair ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened architects and building engineers don’t want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” says Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found in a frisonne agricultural company an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, one millimetre thick synthetic membrane has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we're saving time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, and then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and potted ficus.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they contribute above all to the maintenance of the ideal level of humidity of the literary mountain air.
Gifts for the New Soul
“It’s incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books lies below a glass bell, the sun only illuminates the interior for a short time, even on good weather days.
The thick wooden beams mounted crosswise with respect to the glass facade serve as sun visors, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
Fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was also there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "soul at last found."
A few weeks ago, during the inauguration, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure made it possible to fill the voids of the library which was not yet completely filled (today, it counts 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing on all sides.
For architect Winy Maas, “there is nothing worse than a half-empty library.”
“I believe our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it’s just for decoration.”
This is how MVRDV achieved the master discipline called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
She may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "The Germans must play a bigger role."
Germany chose abstention in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinians’ request for observer state status at the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
Why not?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but was not overly critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also chosen abstention in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany find it difficult to take a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so to speak defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans faced several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still groping to find that role, but are on the way to a “more normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Great Britain
What does the term “normal” foreign policy mean for Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions that are independent of those of the United States and European partners, including on national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of the other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position on the Middle East conflict and its abstention from the United Nations vote?
First, Germany has important markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to offend public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a determining factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, because it is not an exclusively one-sided relationship.
But this is at least a determining factor in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany harm its relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that the Europeans and the Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think the divide is not so severe as it was in the case of the Libyan issue.
Germany may even be more respected.
Indeed, Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government can of course not defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at Obama’s relationship with Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you’ll notice that Obama is far from over-enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policies.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think that makes things any easier for the Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
They cannot therefore be part of a wider political line and must assert their unique position.
This is what they are currently doing on the issue of the euro.
In my view, Germany will take on the role of a locomotive in the future and push Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, especially because of its relations with Israel.
This question has always been delicate.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware of the fact that they must play a role that further marks their independence.
Does Germany see itself as a major player on the international scene, does Germany only want to take on a key role?
Or is she still struggling to take on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country is still struggling to play a more important role.
If we look, for example, at the euro crisis, we notice that whenever Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German sentiments are heard.
It doesn't make things any easier for the Germans.
In fact, it's always the same problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
She has to deal with neighbors and a wide variety of opinions, and that's not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European politics is only diminishing, but at the moment, the EU is not filling this void, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they do not like it, even if it is unpleasant to them and if they are only less appreciated, it is life!
Stephen Szabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America analyze together the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that the undertaking bearing its name cannot lodge a complaint.
And even if she could, it is not certain that she would win the case.
“It’s becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their brands in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer with Taylor Wessing, a law firm that specializes in property infringement in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Impersonators only need a few extra letters to be able to register their marks.
So instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sporting goods.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet containing the registrations made at the Beijing Trademark Office.
