In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell virtually nothing but counterfeits.
Pattloch’s cases, however, are different: his constituents charge him with tackling the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese speak of "Bang Mingpai", parent brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is with this term that women are designated who marry rich men.
Chinese officials say they have nothing to complain about.
“It’s bad for business, we have to fight this trend,” Pattloch demands.
“The brand is watered down, the singularity disappears, the damage to reputation is huge.”
The financial losses and legal costs are in the millions for the sectors concerned, especially with regard to expensive flagship products.
According to data from market analysis company CLSA, China is the world’s third fastest growing luxury goods market with an annual volume of 15 billion euros.
However, it is not easy to delete questionable registrations from the trademark register and these procedures are expensive.
These can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch reports on the trials in which the court dismissed the complaint, because after a long period of time, the criticized denomination had become a “market reality.”
Pattloch explains that if the complainant is not lucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarist because he would have harmed his mark in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the same company that had just bought concrete pump producer Putzmeister.
This is why the Chinese can use an emblem that resembles the Mercedes star.
Volvo's buyer Geely used a blue-and-white logo reminiscent of BMW before, but the conflict was resolved and Geely had to change it.
The fashion house Lacoste had lost to plagiarists from Hong Kong and Singapore who had reoriented the famous crocodile’s gaze in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
However, the CTMO trademark office in Beijing admits to having experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, the office would have gone last year from an "emergency situation in the course of work to a restored normality".
Thus, the number of unprocessed opposition proceedings would have decreased by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 such cases have reportedly been closed, an increase of 75% over the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81,500 proceedings remain pending at the Office.
Acting is expensive
As is often the case in China, the figures are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the agency, this is a record and it means that China is at the top of the ranking for the tenth time in a row for the number of new filings in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal trademarks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the agency reportedly recorded 1.8 billion yuan in registration fees.
In other words, each record brought in an average of 1.280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as illustrated by the case of the German family company Freudenberg.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting a Chinese plagiarist.
Certainly, the Germans were able to get the illegal manufacture of vehicle components to be suspended.
However, the impersonator was able to maintain his Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
“It’s our fault, because surnames cannot be protected in Germany,” says Hanno Wentzler, CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The trade mark office had therefore rejected the Munichers' objection.
Freudenberg won the case in the following two instances, but the opposing side continues to fight until today.
Vigilance is required
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, he believes in a positive outcome of the trial and praises the professionalism of the judges.
Nevertheless, he adds: "the procedure is long, trying and costs us a lot of time and money."
It is also difficult to assess internal costs, and the archives department has even had to review the actions of the past hundred years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg even unsuccessfully offered the opposing party a "big six-figure sum" to settle the dispute.
“That’s how we see what it means to us,” Wentzler says.
The dangers of the Far East even threaten to spill over into Europe.
This would be the case if imitators in this region ensured the exploitation of the unprotected marks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to deposit Freudenberg’s name in Germany for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long since abandoned this sector, but it was still able to prevent the deposit.
Wentzler adds: "vigilance is in order."
He and Pattloch advise German companies to exercise great caution in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, according to them, to rely on international trademark law, rather foreigners should “register also in China everything that is likely to be protected”, as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, the costs may be much higher than those of registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle in the last act of his legal drama, the company would have to pay licensing fees to the opposing party for the use of his own name, as Wentzler explains.
Otherwise, we would lose our place in the segment of the market in question.
