It's Monday night, the Imbongi choir is rehearsing a new song in the music room of the Heidelberg Institute of Medical Psychology.
Fifty singers from 23 to 69 years old have come, from the geneticist in human medicine to the man at home.
"Om'Obani" is not an easy piece, each chorister has different lyrics, all in a very exotic language: Zulu, a language spoken by 11 million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and parts of Swaziland.
