Norway’s rakfisk: is it the most fragrant fish in the world?
The five million people who inhabit Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe, but also in the world.
Could the secret of the country's success be linked to the locals' appetite for an extremely fragrant fish?
Take advanced cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of wet and dirty football clothes.
Wait a week.
And you get the disturbing smell of rakfisk, one of Norway’s most popular dishes.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about 3 hours from Oslo.
It snows, the landscape is spectacular - and this smell, omnipresent, permeates the air.
The rakfisk consists of trout sprinkled with salt and fermented in water for a duration - depending on the smell you want it to exhale - which can go up to a year.
When darkness sets in and it’s cold, Norwegians gather in droves to attend a festival here in Fagernes dedicated to this incredible culinary specialty.
“You eat raw, then you swallow a glass of aquavit,” says Havard Halvarsen, a full-time local firefighter who is also known as “Rakfisk General,” who runs the festival.
Around us, people swallow small pieces of fish and put on a large amount of drink.
“Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk,” Havard adds.
The drink kills the smell.
I'm trying a few pieces.
If you can avoid getting it under your nose, it’s not bad – it’s reminiscent of sushi that would have spent long hours on a bus.
The rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, before the invention of refrigeration, the fish was immersed in barrels of airtight water, then salted in autumn.
Then, during the winter, once well fermented, the fish came out and - undoubtedly with the senses diminished by alcohol - eaten.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country to find work, mainly emigrating to the United States.
Now the population is growing rapidly - over 13% are immigrants, attracted by full employment, high wages and a comprehensive health care system.
The Swedes, their old rivals whose country was not so long ago richer than Norway, cross the border to come and work.
Rakfisk is seen as something important, a vital, though fragrant, element of Norway's past.
This is one of the most expensive dishes.
But everything is expensive - a pint of beer or a sandwich will cost you $10 each.
Norway does not often feature in international news, which is not to his displeasure.
Here, people are not willing to talk about Anders Breivik, the right-wing racist extremist who shot 77 people, including women and children.
When they talk about this killing, they talk about the "July 22 incident".
The Norwegians find it difficult to accept that in their peaceful country one of their own could have committed such an act of barbarism.
Since the early 1970s, Norway owes its wealth to its oil and gas industry, one of the largest in the world.
“But oil is not the only reason for our success,” says Anna, our waitress, with blonde hair and piercing blue eyes, the image of Nordic well-being, with a rakfisk platter in her hand.
We are - how do you say - prudent people.
His English, like that of most people who live here, is perfect.
We are discreet, we do not like to be noticed.
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution - everything except a small percentage of money from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When other countries threw the money out the window, in the years leading up to the international financial crisis, Norway kept its purse strings tight.
“As long as you can ski in winter and hike in summer, we’re happy,” says Anna.
“Not to mention the rakfisk,” she adds in a carefree laugh.
I stand under the snow and queue up to buy myself something to eat - I got my dose of rakfisk.
On the menu, a burger composed of elk, a real discovery, it's excellent.
But tonight, the smell of fish is everywhere.
The hotel I am staying at is one of the many places where rakfisk is served for dinner and where one can vote for the best of them – or perhaps for the most fragrant of them.
There is a TV show where the presenter wears a bow tie, surrounded by rakfisk plates.
It looks like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score did you give to the best fish in the Thor-Juergen mountains?"
"Here are our points, Havard."
We hear laughter and applause.
A man falls from his chair, perhaps because of the abuse of aquavit.
Or maybe it's because of the fish fumes.
Mexican Enrique Pena Nieto has a tough start.
As incoming President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office in Mexico, Will Grant of the BBC is interested in the difficulties that await him and the expectations of the people, which are many.
Road traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad at the moment.
In a city where traffic jams are legion in normal times, a safety dam has been set up since Monday, blocking several key road accesses in the capital and causing real chaos on the roads.
Nevertheless, the aim was not to prevent people from going to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching Parliament.
Next Saturday, the new president of Mexico, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential scarf to become the new president at the head of the nation.
A complicated task awaits him.
Mexico's economy is doing well, the results of outgoing President Felipe Calderon, but the country is in the throes of a drug war that has already claimed the lives of about 60,000 people in six years.
“My government has made a commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence,” Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve this goal.
Before joining the U.S. president, Pena Nieto was governor of the state of Mexico.
A very populous and sprawling state that encircles the capital. In his preferred land, opinions about this new leader are divided.
A direct man
In the bucolic town of Valle del Bravo, for example, it is inscribed in everyone’s memory.
The locals attribute it to the development of tourism and infrastructure in the municipality.
To reach the city you can take one of the new highways of M Pena Nieto, a major improvement has been made to these roads, once bumpy and full of crevices.
Plaques bearing his name hang outside a new sports complex and an impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
“We are counting on him to bring about lasting change,” said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a member of Congress and of Mr Pena Nieto’s party, the PRI.
In terms of security and economy in particular, we hope for a real change that our country so badly needs.
