However, this is exactly what the family was denied.
The authorities treated me as if I were an old gossip, a troublemaker, a whimper.
They want us to accept what they say and keep quiet.
“But it’s not normal that there are so many irregularities and omissions,” she said.
When President Pena Nieto receives his scarf on Saturday, it will be accompanied by a heavy responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by crime in Mexico over the past six years, and the new president has made a promise that he will make it his priority during his tenure.
“I hope he’ll be as good as he was when he was governor,” Olvera, a member of Congress, told Valle del Bravo.
However, this is exactly what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to counter Bradley Manning's claims of abuse during detention.
The trial is about Manning being held in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants to dismiss the case on the grounds that Manning's detention took place under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to show on Friday that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of being behind the largest leak of confidential information in the history of the U.S. military -- missed many opportunities to complain about the mistreatment he claims to have suffered during his military detention.
During cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney Maj. Ashden Fein claimed that recordings of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a motion demanding that the Manning case be closed on the grounds that the detention was in very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place a day after Manning testified his desire to commit suicide while in custody.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At Friday’s hearing, Fein examined with Manning the forms officers had filled out after meeting with Manning, during his detention in Quantico military prison, where he was subjected to maximum prison segregation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment his guards had given him was “excellent” and that the treatment he had had at the prison was overall “very professional.”
There were no complaints of ill-treatment on the forms, although officers questioned him directly about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had verbally expressed concerns about certain issues and that visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the issues raised.
“They wrote ‘no problem’ (after addressing the concerns), and yet that didn’t mean I didn’t raise any issues,” Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment during a January 2011 interview with the special commission that met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to have his restrictive status changed to indicate a “risk of injury.”
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close monitoring for suicide risk -- for his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was fine, and I wanted to be stripped of that status... in order to benefit from a better quality of life from my perspective,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the Marine Corps base military prison in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he considered committing suicide while in Kuwait and fainted once because of the heat.
He added that the fact of not being kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was going on in the rest of the world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage,” Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 9 p.m. and sometimes more than 11 p.m. -- without company.
Manning also added that the only items he had were a mattress, blanket, flip flops, clothes and his glasses.
He tried to stay in motion because sleeping or lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning also said that when he tried to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so they could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint about Manning's treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked all night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other detainees one morning, during the call.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a blanket during the call.
During the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he had inferred from his guard's order that he had to let go of his cover that might have hidden his nudity, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to let go.
Manning testified Thursday that he was forced to sleep naked the night before, as he allegedly tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underpants or flip-flops to hurt himself, but that he had not.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account his experiences during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence should he be found guilty in a court martial, a trial that should be held early next year.
The defense said Manning plans to plead guilty to the lesser offenses and fight to drop other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning has been detained in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information relating to national defense.
If all charges are upheld, he is liable to life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis
He says many were forced to leave Mexico because of lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame those who left; they remind Mexicans of difficult times, he said.
Navarrette says that Mexico-Americans find themselves caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, arriving in the lobby, in front of the customs and immigration services, I felt lost.
Signs indicated two ways: one for the Mexicans, another for the Extranjeros.
I remained motionless for several seconds, not knowing which line to go to.
I grew up in central California, where I was called the "Mexican" all my life.
It’s an ethnic qualifier, just like the one my friends in Boston use when they call themselves “Irish,” or my friends in New York when they call themselves “Italian.”
Then I became Mexican-American.
But here it was Mexico.
And on the land where my grandfather was born, there is no need for a special qualifier or a hyphen.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to handle an interview in either language.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a Native American, and I can't lose my American accent.
So I took my U.S. passport and headed for the "Foreigners" line.
I thought about that time of the week when Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited President Obama in the White House.
Generally, when the leaders of these two countries meet, their favorite themes are immigration, drugs, and trade.
Pena Nieto also wanted to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one of the reasons why Mexicans stay in Mexico rather than risk the United States.
He wants to ally with the United States and Canada, and create a Union for trade on the model of the European Union, but in North America.
And Pena Nieto is committed to continuing the war against the drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not provide further details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of bitterness.
Most Americans probably never thought about the fact that in 1848, the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to give up half of their territory in writing at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think in terms of centuries, and not minutes, memories are everywhere.
Therefore, as soon as a U.S. official makes any criticism of Mexico, you begin to hear -- in the Mexican press, and among the elites -- complaints about how Americans are undermining their neighbor's sovereignty.
And Montezuma's kids are looking for a fight.
And yet, for Mexico, the most difficult relationship is with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
You want us to talk about bitterness?
There are a lot of them.
Mexico has its winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities and others for whom the country does not.
The only reason that explains the large number of Mexican ancestors in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio, is that at some point in our family tree, a person, perhaps a relative or grandparent, found no opportunity in Mexico and had to go to the North.
And more often than not, this person matched a typical profile -- dark, uneducated skin, from a poor village, etc.
We are their descendants, and we are loyal to them.
Not Mexico.
And even though we are living the American dream right now, that we have gone to good schools and we have good situations, we must never lose sight of the fact that this is the American dream that we are living, and not that of Mexicans.
Our identity is sometimes troubled, but our loyalty is obvious.
We grant it to the United States.
On the other hand, we know that part of the Mexican elite among the ruling class does not like us.
The feeling is reciprocated.
We remind them of a humiliating defeat and they kill us as if we were individuals of lower stock and not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
For them, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families had not failed when they lived in Mexico, they would never have left.
And we wouldn’t find ourselves stuck on the right side of the fence, living comfortably in the United States, but like lost souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally emigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there is friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans, because Mexicans claim their identity more firmly and Mexican-Americans are upset about it.
Although she is a U.S. citizen, she feels part of two countries.
On the other hand, many Mexican-Americans I know do not feel like they are part of one country or the other.
We love the music of the Mexican band, Los Tigres del Norte, but also that of Bruce Springsteen.
We have the best of both worlds, but we are not rooted in either.
In Mexico, we are considered Americans.
And in the United States, we are considered Mexicans.
And now, to further complicate the relationship, as I learned during my stay, some Mexican leaders and part of the intelligentsia want to get closer to the Diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as makeshift ambassadors for Mexico, representing its interests in the United States.
We will have to explain to our American compatriots that Mexico is a beautiful country that must be visited and put pressure on political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure.
It won't happen.
There's too much bitterness.
And, considering the pervasive wage inequality, corruption and drug-related violence, many of us are not convinced that this is a fantastic country.
You're going to have to manage on your own, amigos.
That's normal.
If some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, they must therefore accept that some Mexican-Americans still resent them the way their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexicans" than I thought.
Old quarrels, new Middle East
The cease-fire between Israel and Hamas is yet another failure for peace.
Can there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed seems to indicate that such hope is in vain.
While the same futile arguments persist about who started, dozens of buildings have been reduced to dust; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; and, for the first time, rockets fired from Gaza have landed near Tel Aviv, the metropolis of Israel, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But while Israelis and Palestinians seem stuck in their old conflict, all around them, the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring has shattered everything, and whether we like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis are caught up in this regional upheaval.
Perhaps their struggle will intensify a little more.
Still, there is every reason to think that it could help them get out of this deadly impasse.
A war that makes no losers or winners
At first glance, it seems difficult to be optimistic.
Although the ceasefire agreed on 21 November is still in place, this week’s fighting has strengthened supporters of the force on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to give up, even if Gaza has suffered a beating.
Having killed some of its leaders and pushed Gaza’s 1.7 million people back into one of the most miserable and overcrowded corners of the planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining ground on the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently in the hands of their rivals Fatah, the other more moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders might say that time is their ally.
The influence of Islamists in the Arab world is growing, and Hamas has made rich and powerful friends.
Turkey, a burgeoning regional power, once Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has stood up for Hamas; as has Qatar, one of the Golf’s wealthiest and most dynamic states.
Hamas members gloat and say the Islamist crescent bends around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, where Hezbollah’s militia exercises dominance, through Syria, where Islamist-leaning rebels can topple Bashar al-Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And most importantly, on Israel’s southern flank, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under the presidency of Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and central of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time to devote to Hamas.
On the other hand, the Muslim Brotherhood is a cousin of Hamas, and its leaders rely more easily on public opinion.
In future diplomacy, Hamas can emerge as an important actor that can no longer be ruled out even by Israel and America.
Meanwhile, supporters of Israel’s hard line will draw the opposite conclusions.
In military terms, Hamas has been boxed.
The Iron Dome missile interceptor system proved its effectiveness and many Hamas missiles were destroyed.
Israelis will be able to sleep on both ears – for a while.
In terms of diplomacy, America is renewing its unwavering support; and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest wave of violence.
But above all, Israel prospered, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who totally ignored the peace process.
Although rocket fire from Gaza has killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has been spared suicide bombings, including thanks to the separation barrier that encroaches on the West Bank, the main piece of what could be a Palestinian state, and protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite their illegality under international law.
Netanyahu, whose Likud party merged with an even more hawkish party, that of leader Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the January 22 election, has the beautiful part.
Why pamper these damn Palestinians by giving them a state?
If they ruled the West Bank, would they not launch rockets, as their compatriots did in Gaza?
It is best to keep them behind this wall and hit them as soon as they come out their head.
Perhaps the hardliners will win; but the Arab Spring may be a game-changer.
Even if Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere do not appreciate Israel, their priority will be to tackle the problems in their own countries.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the local superpower will not help the new Arab governments to fix their economies.
Mr. Morsi has worked with Barack Obama to secure a ceasefire, which bodes well -- and could mark the beginning of something.
Israelis should also think about the future.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination could create a powder keg that is bound to explode one day in the territories occupied by Israel – much like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already weakening democracy in the Jewish state, and demographics are exacerbating this problem as the Arab population grows.
The bloody missions against Gaza every two or three years to ring Hamas will have a diplomatic value.
Both sides need to be pushed by those on the outside.
The answer remains that advocated by reasonable people on either side, and by most of the outside world and by this newspaper: two states, with a cession of territory by Israel in exchange for security.
One hope, small and short-term, is that the ceasefire will provide an opportunity for outsiders to advocate for this cause.
Egypt, which must now work to end the flow of arms to Gaza, along with Turkey and Qatar, is in a better position than ever to persuade Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state in accordance with the 1967 borders with land swaps and a shared Jerusalem.
Arabs from outside countries should also pressure Hamas and Fatah to unite.
This would contribute much more to the establishment of a Palestinian state than the forthcoming proposal of a pseudo-state at the United Nations.
Mr. Obama also has a vested interest in Israel agreeing to negotiate.
