Back in the White House, he seems equally reluctant to establish one.
It's a very narrow vision.
The stability of the Middle East is a vital issue for America.
This requires a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Laws for neutral cigarette packs have come into force in Australia
Warnings and photos of diseased organs cover the dark green packages which are all identical, regardless of brand
This law, which came into force in Australia, is a world first, with logos and colors replaced with a dark olive green and horrible photos of sick organs and depictions of children and babies whose illnesses were caused by their parents' smoking.
Apart from the different photos and health warnings, the only difference between the packages, since this Saturday, is the name of the brand, printed in small print on all packages.
It is the strictest system in the world for tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government said the goal was to deter young people from smoking by removing any glamorous portrayals.
Studies have shown that if people did not start smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99 percent chance that they will never start.
“Even when they are very young, children understand the message conveyed by tobacco manufacturers through their brand image,” said federal health minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that found, for example, that children associated the crown of a logo with a princess.
While Australia has the lowest smoking rate in the world and these changes have little impact on multinational profits, other countries are considering a similar approach.
The tobacco industry has lobbied against this law.
Tobacco manufacturers said it would boost black market trade, which will give easier access to cheaper cigarettes.
“There will be adverse consequences from this legislation,” said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will sell far more counterfeit cigarettes on the streets of Australia.
Others said the law boosted their activity.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, said the demand for cigarette cases, including silicone to hide the horrible packaging, has risen sharply two months ago since British American Tobacco, Britain’s Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco challenged the law and lost in Australia’s high court.
Ha said Zico has sold 6,000 of them to wholesalers and is awaiting stock renewal.
For us, business is good.
