The problem is that it has been defined, and debated, in different ways, said John D. Eastwood, associate professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After scouring numerous publications and submitting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience of "wanting to do something but not being able to engage in a satisfying activity."
What differentiates boredom from apathy, he says, is that the person is not undertaking a task although they would like to.
With apathy, he says, there is no desire to do anything.
What is at the heart of boredom, he said, is “the interruption of the attention process, associated with a sullen mood and the feeling that time is passing slowly.”
Boredom can strongly resemble depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while the two may be related, people who are bored tend to think the problem comes from the environment or the world, while depressed people think the problem comes from them.
Sometimes we think that we are bored when it is actually a problem of concentration.
As part of their study, “The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention,” which was published in the journal “Perspectives on Psychological Science” in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues highlighted an older experiment in which participants listened on tape, the voice of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups heard, coming from the room next door, the too high sound of a TV show that had no connection, others just heard the TV show, and the third group did not hear the soundtrack at all.
Those who heard TV at a low sound level said they were more bored than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, but didn't know why, and attributed this problem of concentration to boredom.
When you’re trying to focus on a difficult or challenging task, an interruption of attention can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
On the other hand, when performing a boring task, “like looking at objects on a timeline, music can help you not get bored.”
In fact, he says, now we know that when you squirm or scribble, these gestures, often seen as signs of boredom, are actually a good way to stay physically more alert.
