The Hardest Job in the World: The Human Mules by Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and their health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through the steep stone trails.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living carrying sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfuric gas emanating from the bowels of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After collecting large sulfur rocks, which weigh nearly 70 kilos in total, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep paths.
There are only 250 meters up to the summit of the volcano which rises to 2,386 meters above sea level, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a turtle-like pace, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a fatal fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 euro cents for every kilo of sulfur mined.
Once at the top, they make their way between tourists who photograph them as if they were circus beasts, and carrying heavy baskets painfully, they walk the 3 kilometers to the scale that a mining company installed a little below at 1,850 meters above sea level.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, we can tell, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) per kilo of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to the petrochemical industry since this ore is very present in daily life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even serves to whiten sugar.
“As we carry around 70 kilos, we earn around 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip,” says Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each takes him 3 hours and he finishes exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is three times what it would gain in the fields.
“The income of the miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” says the porter who once worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) a day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her back to Java to convert."
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At 27, he spent three of his life defying danger on the Kawah ljen, but the sulfur has already begun to make him pay the bill although he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
That’s the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
“I’m going to work for another two years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French,” he said.
Wounded by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but, instead, he does the job of a mule.
It shares an unsanitary wooden house with other wearers, rises every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulfur does not stop gushing at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater by lighting himself with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load the baskets of sulfur on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to porters who work on their own and are paid by weight.
In addition, they do not touch a penny of 30,000 rupees (2.50 euros) of surcharge per camera, in addition to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros), which the guards of this natural park charge to tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This job is for the beasts, not the humans,” protested Madrusin, a 42-year-old corpulent porter who has been working at Kawah Ijen for thirty years, since he left college.
Able to carry up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will not stop working "as long as he can", because he needs money to raise his 3 sons, between 10 and 18 years old.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke that come out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases ... to which are obviously added their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and shoulders, deformed by the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, 53-year-old Unainik can only load 50 kilos.
Every day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a goat trail invaded by weeds.
“I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life,” says Unainik, opening his mouth well, revealing several missing teeth.
The eldest of his five children, aged 30, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the most difficult jobs in the world: the one made by the human mules of the Kawah ljen volcano.
