UNASUR summit ended without Lima Declaration made public
The VI Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 proxies present.
Efe tried repeatedly to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially signaled that it would be disclosed after the conclusion of the summit, then claimed that it would be published at any time on the Peruvian government’s website.
When asked about the text, they reported that its content had been exposed by Peru’s President, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated between the journalists was that given by the press officers of some of the governments of Unasur who attended the appointment, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document leaked during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more important information.
Later, Peru’s presidency sent an email to the media with the “final declaration” of the summit, but it was President Humala’s speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd Summit of South America-Arab Countries (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although this was requested by the press, it had also not disseminated the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as had been previously announced.
On the official website of the ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to put in place safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited as much as possible the obtaining of information.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Court of The Hague that decides a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastian Pisera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ’s decision to hear the pleas of both parties in Lima’s lawsuit against Santiago, which begins Monday in The Hague.
“We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we are bringing before this international court today,” Humala said.
“Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country respectful of international law, peaceful resolution of controversies, treaties and international tribunals,” President Pisera added, giving a handshake to President Humala, next to the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Pact of Bogota by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of this international tribunal, after a decision on the maritime limits with Nicaragua that it considered seriously erroneous.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chavez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the rendezvous.
Host President Ollanta Humala was tasked with opening deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the action lines for 31 projects had been set between the South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of Unasur would put in place "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions to improve access to medicines, access to low-cost Internet throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With Europe in crisis, “economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help increase our productive matrix and glimpse a better future for our people,” concluded President Humala.
“We have decided to focus on a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” the Peruvian president said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were on the cross-cutting axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador although he did not give further details.
Similarly, the outcome document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that this country’s electoral process will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations,” from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and with good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through an ICJ judgment requested by Bogota.
"It's possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
“We are going to revise all these paths, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask to have a discussion with this country,” he said.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will deal with this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos said.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City, where they plan to attend the inauguration of the country’s new president, Enrique Pena Nieto.
Similarly, as part of the summit, the bloc’s defence ministers will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of Unasur, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
