He proposes to reorient this inefficient distribution; that condoms not only be sold at counters, but that they be found in public washroom vending machines and in places frequented by young people.
It is not about encouraging promiscuity.
Nor is it a question of paying them the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio Gonzalez had replied when asked if there would be a distribution of condoms within his administration.
“This is not how sexuality works, the best is to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active,” he said.
The numbers in Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The State is the fourth largest in the country in terms of new and cumulative cases of AIDS and 13th in terms of the number of HIV patients.
92% of infections occur sexually, 6% through the blood and 2% through the perinatal route.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV, since for every registered case, there are 4 or 5 people who ignore it.
A U.S. court decision on appeal ignores the restructuring of Vitro Group’s debt through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico, setting a bad precedent for all domestic companies with branches in the neighboring country and solvency problems.
So it seems that the procedures for the survival of companies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the country with the star-studded banner, contrary to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the judgment handed down on June 15 by Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the North District of Texas, leaves Mexican companies defenseless against the possibility of embargoing their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico’s top glass maker to sue the U.S. Supreme Court based on three inconsistencies.
First, while the case judge reports that creditors must register under U.S. bankruptcy law, the Fifth Circuit Appeals Court, sitting in New Orleans, says the main proceeding is formalized commercial bankruptcy in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing cooperation in international proceedings in cases of insolvency of companies with a transnational profile.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for Uniform International Commercial Law was created for this purpose by taking the American Law Institute as arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment establishes that without the intercompany vote, recognized in the critical mass of the commercial bankruptcy, the debts incurred by Vitro subsidiaries towards the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
