The most serious is that the court ignored a document sent by the government of Mexico on behalf of the amicus curiae ("friend of the court") detailing Vitro's procedure under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act, noting that it freed Vitro from the conventions signed by both countries to bring it up to the level of paragraph 15 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Act.
In addition, he pointed out that the country had complied with the United Nations Commission on International Trade principles, i.e. the rules for cross-border insolvency cases, which guaranteed fairness for debtors and creditors.
